'''Ellen Martin Henrotin''' (6 July 1847 - 29 June 1922) was a wealthy American society matron, labor reform activist, club leader and social reformer affiliated with social welfare and [[Women's suffrage in the United States|suffrage movement]]s.<ref name="lib.harvard.edu">{{cite web|title=Henrotin, Ellen M. (Ellen Martin), 1847-1922. Papers of Ellen Martin Henrotin, 1865-1921: A Finding Aid|url=http://oasis.lib.harvard.edu/oasis/deliver/~sch00621|publisher=Harvard University Library|accessdate=29 May 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Gordon|2013|p=232}}{{sfn|Kelley|Sklar|Palmer|2009|p=90}}

==Early years and education==
Henrotin was born on 6 July 1847 in [[Portland, Maine]], the daughter of Edward Byam and Sarah Ellen Martin, and the second of six children.{{sfn|O'Sullivan|Gallick|1975|p=56}} During her youth, she lived in England, and attended schools in [[London]], [[Paris]], and [[Dresden]], 1860-68.{{sfn|University of Illinois-Urbana-Champaign|1918|p=976}} Returning to the US in 1868,{{sfn|Clapp|2010|p=24}} she married [[Charles Henrotin]], one of the founders of the [[Chicago Stock Exchange]], on September 2, 1869 in Chicago. Their children were Edward Clement (born 1871), Charles Martin (born  1876), and Morris Bates (born 1885).{{sfn|University of Illinois-Urbana-Champaign|1918|p=976}}

==Career==
She served as Vice President of the Congress Auxiliary of the [[World's Columbian Exposition]], 1893; President of the [[General Federation of Women's Clubs]], 1894-98; President of [[Fortnightly of Chicago|Fortnightly Club of Chicago]]; as well as Trustee, [[University of Illinois]], 1912-17. She was decorated by the Sultan of Turkey with the order of the Chefakat, 1893; made an Officier de 1'Académie by the French Republic, 1899; decorated by Leopold II, Chevalier de l'Ordre de Léopold, 1904. She was a member of the Friday Club; [[Chicago Woman's Club]]; and [[City Club of Chicago|Woman's City Club]]. 

Henrotin lived at 1215 [[Madison Avenue]], in [[New York City]].{{sfn|University of Illinois-Urbana-Champaign|1918|p=976}} She died on 29 June 1922 in [[Cherry Plain, New York]].<ref name="Encyclopedia">{{cite web |title=Henrotin, Ellen Martin (1847–1922) |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/women/dictionaries-thesauruses-pictures-and-press-releases/henrotin-ellen-martin-1847-1922 |website=Dictionary of Women Worldwide: 25,000 Women Through the Ages, Encyclopedia.com |accessdate=30 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

