{{UK Mainland UNESCO World Heritage Sites image map|}} [[File:Londonderry (1).jpg|thumb|[[Londonderry railway station]] on the scenic [[Belfast-Derry railway line]] run by [[Northern Ireland Railways]].]]
The [[United Kingdom]] is the world's [[World Tourism Rankings|6th biggest tourist destination]], with 36.115&nbsp;million visiting in 2015. US$22.072&nbsp;billion was spent in the UK by foreign tourists. [[VisitBritain]] data shows that the USA remains the most valuable inbound market, with American visitors spending £2.1&nbsp;billion in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/home/world-news/article/16044975|publisher=Sky News|title=Fears US Debt Crisis Will Hit UK Tourism|year=2011|accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> Nevertheless, the number of travellers originating from Europe is much larger than those travelling from North America: 21.5&nbsp;million compared to 3.5&nbsp;million American/Canadian visitors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/cci/nugget.asp?id=352|publisher=Office for National Statistics|title=Office for National Statistics – Overseas residents' visits to the UK|year=2010|accessdate=2011-08-14}}</ref>
The country's principal tourist destinations are in [[London]], e.g. the [[Tower of London]] is one of the most visited attractions in the country.<ref name=ALVA>{{cite web|url=http://www.alva.org.uk/visitor_statistics/|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120194452/http://www.alva.org.uk/visitor_statistics/|archivedate=2012-01-20|df=}}</ref>
== Domestic tourism == Domestic tourism remains the biggest component of tourist spending in the UK, with 2008 expenditures totalling £21,881&nbsp;million, according to VisitBritain.<ref name=VB2009>''[http://www.visitbritain.org/Images/UK%20Tourist%202009_tcm139-191452.pdf UK Tourist 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217185950/http://www.visitbritain.org/Images/UK%20Tourist%202009_tcm139-191452.pdf |date=2015-02-17 }}'', VisitBritain, June 2011</ref> The national statistical agency also estimates that there were 126&nbsp;million trips made in 2009.<ref name=VB2009 /> The busiest period for domestic travel in the UK is during bank holidays and the summer months, with August being the busiest. There is a longstanding history in the UK of travel to coastal resorts such as [[Blackpool]], [[Lancashire]] and [[Swansea]], [[Wales]], with many families staying at accommodation called [[holiday camps]]. This tradition has faded significantly due to competition from overseas [[package tour|package holiday]] operators, rising operational costs, and rapidly changing demand which forced many holiday camps to close in the 1980s and 1990s.
