The '''Union of Russian Writers and Journalists in Paris''' ({{lang-ru|Союз русских писателей и журналистов в Париже}}) was a literary organization formed in July 1920. In 1921 [[Ivan Bunin]] was elected its first chairman, to be succeeded a year later by [[Pavel Milyukov]] who held this post for many years. Another stalwart was [[Vladimir Zeeler]], the Union's secretary for thirty years.
Among the members of the Union's executive committee were [[Aleksey Nikolayevich Tolstoy|Alexey N. Tolstoy]], Sergey Polyakov, [[D.S. Mirsky]]; later [[Alexander Yablonovsky]], [[Konstantin Balmont]], [[Valentin Bulgakov]], [[Alexander Kuprin]], [[Mark Slonim]], [[Sergey Varshavsky]], [[Sergei Efron]], [[Boris Zaytsev (writer)|Boris Zaytsev]], [[Ivan Shmelyov]], [[Mark Aldanov]], [[Don-Aminado]], [[Nadezhda Teffi]], [[Sasha Chyorny]], [[Kirill Zaytsev]], [[Vadim Rudnev]].<ref>Bocharova, Z. [http://www.hrono.ru/biograf/bio_z/zeeler_vf.php Russian Exiles in 1920s-1930s]. Collection of documents // Русские беженцы: проблемы расселения, возвращения на Родину, урегулирования правового положения. (1920-1930-е годы) (Сборник документов и материалов). 2001.</ref> The Union had no publication of its own, the works of its members were published mostly by the Petropolis Publishers, as well as ''Sovremennye Zapiski'' (Contemporary Notes) magazine and ''Vozrozhdenye'' (Revival) newspaper. As the [[Nazi Germany|Nazi German]] troops entered Paris, the Union of Russian Writers and Journalists in Paris disbanded.<ref>[http://www.bsu.by/Cache/pdf/203853.pdf Русский Париж / Russian Paris] (pdf). - www.bsu.by</ref>
